Inscmitynot an excuse for criminals

Carrie Hager

Columnlst

We are all accountable for
what we do, and need to take
responsibility for everything we
do, whether we meant to do it or
not.

Take murder, for instance. A‘

murder is a murder whether it
was premeditated, a spur-of—the-
moment thing, or whether the
person says he just “blacked
out.” It makes no difference. In
any case, a human life has been
taken, and justice needs to be
served. Just because someone is,
or claims to be, a delusional psy-
chotic maniac shouldn’t change
his punishment.

-The insanity plea gained
nationwide attention when John
Hinkley Jr. attempted, and
almost succeeded, in assassinat-
ing Ronald Reagan. It was sup-
posed. to be an open-and-shut
case. It seemed obvious that
someone who attempted to kill
the president should be punished
severely. But jurors in the case
shocked the nation when they

‘found Hinkley to be not guilty by
reason of insanity.

Not guilty? The man almost
killed the president. His mental
status should not have been the
issue. Only the crime should
have been the issue.

I’m not saying that some or
even many defendants aren’t and
shouldn’t be found insane. I just
thinkeven if a person is insane
he is just as guilty. Many say that
the insane criminal can be better
reformed in a , mental hospital,
but that is ridiculous. Just

because someone is insane or
claims to be doesn’t mean he
should be punished less. If it is
needed, mental counseling ’ can
always be provided in jail.

Some argue that serial killers
are insane and aren’t accountable
for what they do. Obviously, any
person who commits multiple
murders, often torturing and
sometimes eating or keeping the
remains of their victims, has
some serious issues. But that
makes no difference. He is still
just as guilty and should be just
as accountable for his actions

Defense lawyers sometimes
use the insanity plea because
they know it is the only possible
way they can get their guilty
client off. (I often wonder how
defenders of Dahmer, Berkowitz
and Gacy can sleep at night,
knowing the monsters they tried
to defend.)

It shouldn’t be like that.
Everyone is responsible for his
actions, regardless of "his mental
state. Saying someone is less
guilty because he is insane is

almost like saying it’s okay that

you killed that innocent victim;
we can forget about justice and
just send you to a nice low-secu-
rity mental hospital for a couple
months. If you tell someone he

isn’t accountable for his actions, '

he will never take responsibility
for what he did, and may kill
again since he can just say that it
wasn’t his fault, he just “blacked
out.” p ..
Susan Biancardi was con-
victed of murdering her teenage
daughter. She shot her daughter
in the "head . while the girl was

THE PITT NEWS

asleep. This is obviously a hor-
rendous crime, and it seemed

’ justice had been served when she
was found guilty of murder. That
was until recently when the U.S.
Supreme Court ordered her a
new trial because it said the jury
didn’t.consider the “not guilty by
reason of insanity” option thor-
oughly.

That is absurd. She obvious-
ly has something wrong with her
if she would shoot‘ her own
daughter, but that doesn’t change
what she did and shouldn’t make
her any less accountable.

If the insanity plea works in
such horriﬁc cases of murder,
how else can it be used? Should
I be able to say that Ididn.’ t do
my homework or'I screamed at
my boss by reason of insanity?
‘Using the insanity plea as a
defense is just ludicrous. The
insanity plea allows for extreme-
ly sick individuals to get off eas-
ily, sometimes not going to. trial
at all.

Many teen mothers who hide
their pregnancy, then kill their
newborns, get, a reduced sen-

tence or no sentence at all,

because they are found to be

- insane at the time the crime was
committed. Many of these‘ mon-
sters are released back into soci-
ety with little more than a slap on
the wrist. ‘ '

The insanity plea should be,

abolished altogether. Criminals
need to be held accountable for
their actions.

