For the first time ever, the NHL has
sent professional players to play for their
respective nations and compete for the
coveted Olympic gold medal.

Unlike the American-dorninated
NBA, the NI-IL’s players are spread out
all over the globe, giving about eight dif-
ferent nations a legitimate shot at a medal.
The players aren’t even staying at a lavish
hotel like the NBA Dream Team boys —
they are staying in the athlete dorms with
all of the other Olympic stars.

In the past, Olympic hockey has been
dominated by the Canadian and Russian
(Soviet) squads, but this time around, the
U.S.A. is one of the most heavily favored
countries to take the gold medal, just like
they did in the 1996 World Cup and in the
1980 Olympic games at Lake Placid, N.Y.

But, with the NHL players competing
seriously against their professional team-
mates, what risks are they willing to take

I to win?

Let’s say, for instance, that Eric
Lindros and Team Canada are in an over-
time battle with the United States for a
medal. John LeClair of Team USA takes
a cross-ice pass deep into the Canadian
zone.

Instantly, Lindros is on him. He has
two options:

A) He could drill LeClair into next
week,-preventing a possible goal and risk-
ing injuiy to a fellow Flyer teammate, and
possibly kissing Lord Stanley’s Cup
goodbye; or,

B) He could let him slide, thus risk-

. ing a possible goal, an Olympic medal

and being labeled the national goat of
Canada.

What would Lindros do?

I wonder if Darius Kasparaitis of
Team Russia will take out Jaromir Jagr’s
(Team Czech Republic) legs if the two
squads meet.

These situations are very possible,
especially with so many players repre-
senting different countries and with the
extremely high level of physical play

A needed to take home a medal.

